[2026-04-18T16:15:42.270Z] [INFO]     "stdout": "title:\tDisable noisy/unused Claude Code features in solve command and Dockerfile\nstate:\tOPEN\nauthor:\tkonard (Konstantin Diachenko)\nlabels:\t\ncomments:\t1\nassignees:\t\nprojects:\t\nmilestone:\t\nnumber:\t1642\n--\n## Summary\n\nClaude Code ships with several built-in features that are noisy, unused, or actively counter-productive when Claude Code is driven non-interactively by our `solve` command and inside the Docker image. We should explicitly disable them.\n\n## Why this matters for `solve`\n\nThe `solve` command runs Claude Code non-interactively and must behave identically across every host it runs on. Host machines (developer laptops, CI runners, Gitpod, user workstations) may have their own `~/.claude/settings.json` with arbitrary overrides — auto memory enabled, feedback surveys on, telemetry, custom hooks, etc. Any of those leak into a `solve` run and make it non-deterministic.\n\nTherefore `solve` must **verify the effective global Claude Code configuration** before handing off to Claude. It must not write a fresh settings file from scratch (that would clobber the user's own preferences), but instead:\n\n1. **Read** the existing global `~/.claude/settings.json`.\n2. **Verify** whether each of the target keys below is already set to the required value.\n3. **Override only the target keys** — preserving every other field the user already has. Same for the `\"env\"` block: merge our required env vars in without dropping user-defined ones.\n\n## Why both env vars AND settings.json (belt-and-suspenders)\n\nClaude Code reads configuration from multiple layers (managed / user / project / local / env). Relying on only one layer is fragile:\n\n- A user's global `~/.claude/settings.json` can *re-enable* something we disabled only via settings.\n- An env var can be unset or stripped by a wrapper shell / CI runner / Docker `ENV` override.\n- Settings keys and env var names occasionally differ in precedence or scope (e.g. `feedbackSurveyRate: 0` vs `DISABLE_FEEDBACK_COMMAND=1`).\n\nFor 100% reliability, every feature below should be disabled **both** via env var **and** via settings.json where a settings key exists. Env vars can live inside settings.json under the `\"env\"` key — documented at https://code.claude.com/docs/en/settings.md#environment-variables — so both controls can be enforced through the same merge step, without requiring a separate shell export.\n\n## Features to disable\n\n### Environment variables\n\n| Variable | Purpose | Source |\n|---|---|---|\n| `CLAUDE_CODE_DISABLE_AUTO_MEMORY=1` | Disable persistent auto-memory files (`~/.claude/projects/*/memory/`). | https://code.claude.com/docs/en/env-vars.md |\n| `CLAUDE_CODE_DISABLE_CRON=1` | Disable `/loop` and `/schedule` skills. | https://code.claude.com/docs/en/env-vars.md |\n| `CLAUDE_CODE_DISABLE_TERMINAL_TITLE=1` | Stop rewriting the terminal title. | https://code.claude.com/docs/en/env-vars.md |\n| `CLAUDE_CODE_DISABLE_CLAUDE_MDS=1` | Prevent loading any `CLAUDE.md` memory files into context. | https://code.claude.com/docs/en/env-vars.md |\n| `CLAUDE_CODE_DISABLE_GIT_INSTRUCTIONS=1` | Remove built-in commit/PR workflow instructions from the system prompt (we inject our own). | https://code.claude.com/docs/en/env-vars.md |\n| `DISABLE_FEEDBACK_COMMAND=1` | Disable the `/feedback` command and bug reporting prompts. | https://code.claude.com/docs/en/env-vars.md |\n\n### `settings.json` fields\n\n| Key | Purpose | Source |\n|---|---|---|\n| `\"autoMemoryEnabled\": false` | Same effect as `CLAUDE_CODE_DISABLE_AUTO_MEMORY`; settings-level mirror. | https://code.claude.com/docs/en/memory.md#enable-or-disable-auto-memory |\n| `\"spinnerTipsEnabled\": false` | Stop showing tips in the spinner while Claude is working. | https://code.claude.com/docs/en/settings.md |\n| `\"awaySummaryEnabled\": false` | Disable session recap when returning to terminal after stepping away. | https://code.claude.com/docs/en/interactive-mode.md |\n| `\"feedbackSurveyRate\": 0` | Probability of post-session feedback surveys; `0` disables them. | https://code.claude.com/docs/en/data-usage.md |\n\n## Where to apply\n\n1. **`solve` command** — before invoking `claude`:\n   - Read the existing global `~/.claude/settings.json` (create an empty object only if the file does not exist).\n   - Verify the four required settings keys and the six required env vars under `\"env\"`.\n   - Override **only** the target keys, preserving all other user-defined fields (including unrelated keys under `\"env\"`).\n   - Also export the six env vars into the Claude subprocess environment (belt-and-suspenders in case the settings merge is ever skipped or the env block is not honored on a given platform).\n   - Log the effective configuration at startup so runs are auditable.\n\n2. **`Dockerfile`** — bake the same configuration in:\n   - `ENV` directives for all six env vars.\n   - Ship a baseline `settings.json` at the image's expected config path containing the four settings keys plus the six env vars under `\"env\"`, so the container starts in a quiet, minimal, deterministic state even if `solve` is bypassed.\n\n## Acceptance criteria\n\n- [ ] `solve` reads and verifies the global `~/.claude/settings.json`, then overrides only the target keys (four settings + six env vars under `\"env\"`), preserving all other user fields.\n- [ ] `solve` also exports the six env vars into the Claude subprocess environment.\n- [ ] `Dockerfile` sets the six env vars via `ENV` and ships a baseline `settings.json` with the four settings keys and the env block.\n- [ ] A `solve` run's Claude stdout/stderr no longer contains spinner tips, away summaries, feedback prompts, or auto-memory system-prompt sections.\n- [ ] Behavior is identical regardless of the host's existing `~/.claude/settings.json`, and unrelated user settings are preserved after a `solve` run.\n\n## References\n\n- Environment variables: https://code.claude.com/docs/en/env-